document.title: Ohio's Early Learning and Development Standards

2C7DE34D965A43A09002935E018879FC.description:
Use full-hand grasp (palmar grasp)
to hold writing tool to make marks
and scribble.

6E73C9C625FF4882BA6D773F018E3451.description:
Recognize familiar sounds (e.g.,
the sound of a particular animal,
a friendâ€™s voice, etc.).

13E692CAD9CC4786880AA08FD127ECCE.description:
Explore sounds of materials
and objects.

86677836EE5745B6B765FB5B312787C6.description:
Point to familiar pictures in books
when labeled by adult.

677AF7C50E6F4324BA6EE078B05B6E68.description:
Actively participate in book reading,
story-telling, and singing.

55BA4473B33448B69E6E94CA86FDD6CD.description:
Participate in and often initiate
basic communications with family
members or familiar others

FF7FF18F79484D18BF99E4E575A7D153.description:
Begin to use single words
and conventional gestures to
communicate with others.

47FFACC6A4924181ACA0C83E9C37A02B.description:
Show understanding of simple
requests and statements
referring to people and objects
around them.

6223C0E29F32468EA139FE7DF2E0097E.description:
Purposefully combine actions to
make things happen.

36F0D9256AEA4101849E15553C7D2070.description:
Observe the physical and
natural world around them

1CDE05477AF3453B9182DFE619E25DA6.description:
Try different things with
objects to see what happens
or how things work

A36CB3EC253A408B97B68339F56A74B0.description:
Prefer familiar adults and
recognize familiar actions
and routines.

8A26674412DB43859A187D6B2D2E7C1E.description: Cognition and General Knowledge: Social StudiesÂ

03E17D950B144B2BAF52303030067688.description:
Explore how things fit and move
in space.

3683A68FB73244E0875B1EF94A230D76.description:
Show awareness of the size
of objects

3E52F70E09AF48F48D35761A5E441005.description:
Match two objects that are the
same and select similar objects
from a group.

17DB3B72D1954567B818DC2871D64528.description:
Notice changes in quantity of
objects (especially ones that can
be detected visually with ease).

3016E953CCFC404BA18454F11397DDFB.description:
Pay attention to quantities when
interacting with objects.

61DDA2F6BE534E3EA76809B3625D808B.description:
With modeling and support,
use simple strategies to solve
problems.

A123F7C4DB114CFA8F6031FA1AE3BEB3.description:
Use one or two simple actions or
objects to represent another in
pretend play.

3B2EB96A2A124028B1B3AADA6B4A47A0.description:
Anticipate the beginning and
ending of activities, songs
and stories

563E63ACA05847C1B4E0CCD0CC83BB78.description:
Mirror and repeat something
seen at an earlier time.

1B348D2CBA774AE9855191011075C431.description:
Recall information over a period
of time with contextual cues.

8BE81BEC3B154755A8182ACAF5C5EFEA.description:
Follow adult intervention and
guidance regarding safety.

A14869952BC94396A96F3D86ED8A6859.description:
With adult assistance, participate
in personal care tasks (e.g., handwashing,
dressing, etc.).

A8B5DA4DED36409C8BD17B098E939F23.description:
Using simple movement skills,
participate in active physical play

71EC549B2ADB49ADBD39D6A9A7AD9234.description:
Point to basic body parts
when asked.

C798AA2A240C405C844CB7DDB6BB0B39.description:
Take and chew small bites/pieces
of finger food.

FE9C4FB6A9FB400DA826683CFE226B28.description:
Use both hands together to
accomplish a task.

AD17B32A8EB74A90B6102D03A380EA29.description: Small Muscle: Touch, Grasp, Reach, Manipulate

1BF4F5BF9F7340B1906EB4C14DDBB281.description:
Move with increasing coordination
and balance, with or without adult
support and/or assistive device.Â

49EEA2F268AA477EA8D9A33825609E69.description:
Seek out experiences with a variety of
materials and art materials based on
preferences and past experiences.Â

4C458EA4000B4AE1861A7A284E2A4E48.description: Expression of Ideas and Feelings Through the Arts

A9939E839FDD40B7AB1C548E862E10F4.description:
Repeat actions intentionally to
achieve goal.

E3E7E758B244431FBB6F666AEF5A4603.description:
Focus on an activity but are
easily distracted.

A6A2FD56C6AA40E5BB2F4907F5349C6A.description:
Approach tasks with repeated trial
and error.

932C5AEEA7C24829AFC8F6331FC826AE.description:
Use a variety of ways to meet
simple goals.

976F5DEACD344397892CD3BF4193E66E.description:
Demonstrate a willingness to try
new activities and experiences.

795E703BE1E94D99A8611EFB02D19B2A.description:
Explore the environment through
a variety of sensory-motor activity.

BCA9439639EF4300AC91823B12671F15.description:
Demonstrate awareness of the
feelings expressed by others.

05E1305179684335BAAA9ED46383B50F.description:
Participate in simple back and
forth interactions with peers for
short periods of time.

ADAF8735AE604812A82A28883C3AEA3B.description:
Participate in routines and
experiences that involve back and
forth interaction with familiar
adults.

46C4A00C18C34CA3B208A43E1B86FAA4.description:
Seek close proximity to familiar
adults for security and support,
especially when distressed.

7DD03D0C313A41AEBA587507FA625476.description:
Explore environment in the
presence of familiar adults with
whom they have developed a
relationship over an extended
period of time.

4C56BC480A0C4AE98A1CDE90F0EF5640.description:
Show a sense of satisfaction when
making things happen.

95ED6D1F20C6400DA90F0E10C85AA831.description:
Respond positively to limits and
choices offered by adults to help
guide behavior.

15278D2757B344A8BE644984C2FD6BEB.description: Comfort self in a variety of ways.

ACD4CB80E4D94E88B6AEB2BE9A80C17A.description:
Recognize self as a unique person
with thoughts, feelings and
distinct characteristics.

883D5C1BC3C147F3AB2676EAEA04A62A.description:
Communicate emotions
purposefully and intentionally,
nonverbally and possibly with
a few familiar words including
complex emotions such as
happiness, sadness, surprise,
dislike, anger, and fear.
